Treat the functional-analytic statement as the infinite-dimensional analogue of a familiar matrix fact, then copy the matrix proof while checking which finite-dimensional steps fail and what replaces them. For example, if you want to prove existence of a bounded inverse, think of the matrix criterion "injective + square implies invertible," and replace "square" by a structural hypothesis such as closed range plus surjectivity, or use the Banach inverse/open mapping theorem. If the goal concerns orthogonality or decomposition, imitate the Euclidean-space proof using projections and orthogonal complements, then replace dot-product arguments by Hilbert-space inner-product identities and closed-subspace theorems. If compact operators appear, think "compact operator = matrix with singular values tending to 0," so the plan should use finite-rank approximation and spectral ideas rather than arbitrary bounded-operator arguments. Write the proof skeleton first in matrix language: choose basis, represent map, identify rank/kernel/image relations, and derive the conclusion. Then translate each step into basis-free language: basis becomes dense span or orthonormal basis, rank/image becomes range/closed range, coordinate estimates become norm estimates, and determinant/eigenvalue arguments become Fredholm, spectral, or compactness tools. The proof plan is complete when every finite-dimensional shortcut has a named infinite-dimensional substitute theorem.
